The {{nihongo|'''Minamikata Kofun cluster'''|南方古墳群||}} is a group of [[Kofun period]] [[kofun|Kofun]]s located in the Amori-cho, Yoshino-cho, Onuki-cho, Maino-cho, Noji-cho neighborhoods of the city of [[:en:Nobeoka, Miyazaki| Nobeoka]], [[:en:Miyazaki Prefecture|Miyazaki Prefecture]] in [[Kyushu]] [[:en:Japan|Japan]]. The tumulus group was collectively designated a [[Monuments of Japan|National Historic Site of Japan]] in 1943. <ref name= "Bunka1">{{cite web |url=https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/203116|title= 南方古墳群|trans-title= Minamikata Kofun cluster|language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=October 1, 2023}}</ref>
==Overview== The Minamikata Kofun Cluster consist of tumuli distributed in the low hills that open to the west of Nobeoka city in the lower reaches of the Gokase River. It has been classified into the Tenka, Onuki, Maino, Yoshino, Noji, and Noda subgroups depending on location. The tumuli date to the early 5th to 6th century, with a variety of burial facilities such as clay coffins, boat-shaped sarcophagi, and side-pit-style stone [[:en:Burial chamber|Burial chamber]]s. At the time of the National Historic Site designation, there were 42 ''kofun'', including five {{nihongo|''[[zenpō-kōen-fun]]''|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|2=ja|3=前方後円墳|4=ko|5=전방후원분|6=zh|7=前方後圓墳|lt=Zenpokoenfun|comement=second one attempting to fix this error|lt=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun}}, which are shaped like a keyhole, having one square end and one circular end, when viewed from above, but despite the protected status there are 38 ''kofun'' remaining in total. These consist of the aforementioned five ''zenpō-kōen-fun'', {{nihongo|''{{ill|Round Kofun|lt=enpun|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Round Kofun|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}''|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun}}-style round tumuli, and one horizontal corridor-type cave-tomb. Minamikata Kofun No. 10 in the Tenkashi group is an "ekagami-style" variation of the ''zenpō-kōen-fun'' with a total length of 78 meters and a diameter of approximately 52 meters at the posterior circular portion. The burial chamber contained a clay coffin covering a wooden coffin, and items such as ''[[magatama]]'' beads, cylindrical beads, bamboo combs, and iron arrowheads and iron swords were found as [[:en:Grave goods|Grave goods]]. On the hill facing south is the Minamikata Kofun No. 1, also an "ekagami-style" tomb with a total length of 71 meters and a diameter of 35 meter at the posterior circular portion, but it has not been [[archaeological excavation|excavated]] because it is site of a [[:en:Shinto shrine|Shinto shrine]] (Tenka Jinja) whose ''[[Honden]]'' is located above the burial chamber. <ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=4311750404}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref>
The history of research into this group of Kofuns is long, and it is said that it began in the late [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]] with the investigation of the Minamikata Kofun No. 24 by Naito Masayasu, the ''[[:en:Daimyō|Daimyō]]'' of [[:en:Nobeoka Domain|Nobeoka Domain]]. In the early 20th century, surface collections were carried out around Minamikata Kofun No. 11, No. 12, and No. 13 and numerous [[:en:Stone tool|Stone tool]]s, beads, gold rings, and [[:en:Sue pottery|Sue pottery]] pottery was found.
The site is approximately ten minutes by car from [[:en:Nobeoka Station|Nobeoka Station]] on the [[:en:Kyushu Railway Company|Kyushu Railway Company]] [[:en:Nippō Main Line|Nippō Main Line]].<ref name="Shiseki"/>
